For this part, you just need to state how many Grade D foods there are with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40 and how many Grade E foods there are with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40; however, it’s useful to think about how that compares/contrasts with your smoothed density curve in Part A.
nrow( subset(food, sqrt(energy_100g) > 40 & nutrition_grade_fr == "d" ) )
## [1] 349
nrow( subset(food, sqrt(energy_100g) > 40 & nutrition_grade_fr == "e" ) )
## [1] 227

From the above output, we can see that there are 349 Grade D foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40, but only 227 Grade E foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40. So, why is the density higher for Grade E foods than Grade D foods?

It’s important to remember that each density is relative only to a particular category. Thus, within Grade E foods specifically, we know that there a relatively high number of foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40. Meanwhile, within Grade D foods specifically, there seems to be a relatively fewer number of foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40. However, this does not imply that the nominal number of Grade E foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40 is greater than the nominal number of Grade D foods with sqrt(energy_100g) > 40.

To put it another way: Each of the above smoothed density curves integrates to 1. Thus, each density is indeed a probability density function in its own righ; these densities aren’t necessarily comparable if the sample sizes between different grades of food are different, which is indeed the case here:

table(food$nutrition_grade_fr)

  1. (10pts) We could use the plot in Part A to visually compare and contrast the distribution of sqrt(energy_100g) for different values of nutrition_grade_fr. Now we’ll consider statistical tests to formally compare these different distributions. For this part, do the following:
  • Test whether sqrt(energy_100g) has the same variance across different values of nutrition_grade_fr. To test whether different groups have the same variance, we use Bartlett’s test via the bartlett.test() function. Specifically, run Bartlett’s test using bartlett.test(outcome~group, data = food), with outcome correctly specified and group correctly specified. After running the test, state your formal statistical conclusion from the test, and explain how you arrived at your answer using Bartlett’s test. In your answer, be sure to state the null hypothesis for this test (if you can’t remember, ask for help or check back at the lecture notes).
bartlett.test(sqrt(energy_100g) ~ nutrition_grade_fr, data = food)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  sqrt(energy_100g) by nutrition_grade_fr
## Bartlett's K-squared = 35.299, df = 4, p-value = 4.034e-07

We see that the p-value is quite small and certainly less than 0.05; thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the variance of sqrt(energy_100g) is the same across all nutrition_grade_fr values, thereby concluding that there is at least one pair of grades that differ in terms of their variance of sqrt(energy_100g).

  • Test whether sqrt(energy_100g) has the same mean across different values of nutrition_grade_fr. To do this, we use one-way ANOVA. So, for this part, use oneway.test(outcome ~ group, data = food), where outcome and group are appropriate specified. Furthermore, within oneway.test(), specify var.equal = FALSE if you think the variances are not equal (according to Bartlett’s test) or specify var.equal = TRUE if you think the variances are equal (according to Bartlett’s test). After running the test, state your formal statistical conclusion from the test, and explain how you arrived at your answer. In your answer, be sure to state the null hypothesis for this test (if you can’t remember, ask for help or check back at the lecture notes).
oneway.test(sqrt(energy_100g) ~ nutrition_grade_fr, data = food, var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  One-way analysis of means (not assuming equal variances)
## 
## data:  sqrt(energy_100g) and nutrition_grade_fr
## F = 390.76, num df = 4.0, denom df = 1014.6, p-value < 2.2e-16

First, note that we set var.equal = FALSE, because we concluded from Bartlett’s test that the population-level variances differ. From this one-way ANOVA test, we see that the p-value is quite small and certainly less than 0.05; thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean of sqrt(energy_100g) is the same across all nutrition_grade_fr values, thereby concluding that there is at least one pair of grades that differ in terms of their means of sqrt(energy_100g).

  1. (15pts) Bartlett’s test and one-way ANOVA are limited in that they cannot tell us which means and variances are different, only that differences may exist. Thus, it’s common to conduct follow-up analyses between subgroups if we believe differences exist. (There can often be issues with multiple testing here, but we’ll ignore that for this lab.) For this question, we’ll focus on Grade B and Grade D foods specifically. It’ll be helpful to define the following dataset:
food.bd = subset(food, nutrition_grade_fr == "b" | nutrition_grade_fr == "d")

Using this dataset, do the following:

  • Run Bartlett’s test using energy_100g as the outcome. State your formal statistical conclusion from this test.
bartlett.test(energy_100g ~ nutrition_grade_fr, data = food.bd)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  energy_100g by nutrition_grade_fr
## Bartlett's K-squared = 82.357, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

We see that the p-value is quite small and certainly less than 0.05; thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the variance of energy_100g is the same between Grade B and Grade D foods, thereby concluding that they differ.

  • Run Bartlett’s test using sqrt(energy_100g) as the outcome. State your formal statistical conclusion from this test.
bartlett.test(sqrt(energy_100g) ~ nutrition_grade_fr, data = food.bd)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  sqrt(energy_100g) by nutrition_grade_fr
## Bartlett's K-squared = 0.65383, df = 1, p-value = 0.4187

Interestingly, we see that the p-value is fairly large: 0.4187, which is larger than 0.05. Thus, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the variance of sqrt(energy_100g) is the same between Grade B and Grade D foods.

As we can see from the above plots, it does indeed appear that the variances of energy_100g are quite different, but not so much the variances of sqrt(energy_100g). The takeaway for this question is that transformations - such as square roots - can sometimes alter our conclusions from hypothesis tests. Indeed, it’s not always the case that the corresponding null hypotheses will align: For example, it is not necessarily the case that \(\sigma^2_B = \sigma^2_D\) implies \(\tilde{\sigma}^2_B = \tilde{\sigma}^2_D\), where the \(\sigma^2\) terms denote the variance of energy_100g, and the \(\tilde{\sigma}^2\) terms denote the variance of sqrt(energy_100g).

For this part, all you need to do is run and state your results from the Bartlett’s tests, as well as produce the plots. However, comparing the two conditional density plots should help you understand the results from the tests. Note: Bartlett’s test is known to be sensitive to non-Normality, in that it has a strong tendency to reject the null hypothesis when data are very non-Normally distributed.

Problem 3: Running and Visualizing KS Tests (35 points)

For this problem, we’ll just work with the energy_100g variable, and NOT the square-root transformation.

  1. (5pts) As a review of previous material, first use the Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) test to assess if energy_100g for Grade D foods follows a Normal distribution. First, let’s define a dataset, food.d, which contains just the Nutrition Grade D foods:
food.d = subset(food, nutrition_grade_fr == "d")

Then, to save you some time, here’s template code you can use to run the test:

mean.est = mean(food.d$energy_100g)
sd.est = sd(food.d$energy_100g)
ks.test(food.d$energy_100g, "pnorm", mean = mean.est, sd = sd.est)
## Warning in ks.test(food.d$energy_100g, "pnorm", mean = mean.est, sd = sd.est):
## ties should not be present for the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  food.d$energy_100g
## D = 0.041825, p-value = 0.2498
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

State the p-value and your formal conclusion from this test.

(Note: You can ignore the warning that’s displayed by the KS test here.)

We see that the p-value is 0.2498; thus, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that energy_100g is Normally distributed for Grade D foods.

  1. (10pts) As discussed in class, the KS test relies on the empirical cumulative distribution functions (CDFs); so, let’s learn how to plot empirical CDFs. To do this, we can use base R. Follow these steps:

  • The ecdf() function computes the empirical CDF. First try typing ecdf(x = food.d$energy_100g).

  • Now plot the empirical CDF by putting the plot() function “around” the ecdf() code you wrote earlier. In other words, your code should look like plot(ecdf(...)).

  • If you try making this plot, it’ll look a bit messy with a lot of dots. To get rid of those dots, write pch = NA within plot() (but not within ecdf()!)

You should end up with the empirical CDF that looks like the “step functions” we’ve been talking about in class this week. Note that the steps are quite small, because the sample size of food.d is pretty large (about 600).

plot(ecdf(food.d$energy_100g), pch = NA)
abline(h = 0.5)

After you’ve made your empirical CDF plot, answer the following in 1-2 sentences: How would you use the plot to report the median of energy_100g for Grade D foods? To help answer this question, draw a horizontal line on your empirical CDF plot by adding abline(h = ?) to your code, where ? is filled in with a value that you think is appropriate to answer this question. Your submission for this part should just be the empirical CDF plot with a horizontal line, as well as 1-2 sentences answering the median question.

As discussed in class, the empirical CDF \(\hat{F}(x)\) denotes the proportion of observations that are less than or equal to some value \(x\). In the above empirical CDF plot, we drew a horizontal line at 0.5; thus, we are considering the point where \(\hat{F}(x) = 0.5\). In other words, we are considering the \(x\) value such that 50% of the data is less than or equal to that value - that is exactly the definition of the median. Thus, we can use the empirical CDF plot to figure out the median by simply picking out the \(x\) value that leads to \(\hat{F}(x) = 0.5\) - i.e., the \(x\) value where the empirical CDF “hits” that horizontal line. More generally, empirical CDF plots can be used to figure out any quantile, not just the 50% quantile.

  1. (10pts) In Part A we used the KS test to test Normality; another test for Normality that’s known to have higher statistical power in detecting non-Normality is the Shapiro-Wilk test. The null hypothesis for the Shapiro-Wilk test is that the data is Normally distributed; thus, the Shapiro-Wilk test can only be used to test Normality, whereas the KS test can be used to test any distribution.

In this part, run the Shapiro-Wilk test for energy_100g within the food.d dataset. To do this, simply uncomment this line of code:

shapiro.test(food.d$energy_100g)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  food.d$energy_100g
## W = 0.98348, p-value = 2.931e-06

You don’t even have to input the sample mean and standard deviation! Also, Martin Wilk is probably sad that this function is just called shapiro.test()…For this part, answer the following after you’ve run the Shapiro-Wilk test:

  • What is your conclusion from the Shapiro-Wilk test? How does this compare to your conclusion from Part A?

For this test, we observe a very small p-value that’s certainly less than 0.05. Thus, according to the Shapiro-Wilk test, we reject the null hypothesis that energy_100g for Grade D foods are Normally distributed, in favor of the alternative that it is not Normally distributed. This differs from the conclusion we made in the KS test, where we failed to reject this null hypothesis.

  • In 1-2 sentences, explain why the Shapiro-Wilk test gives a different p-value from the KS test, with the knowledge that the Shapiro-Wilk test has more power than the KS test.

Because the Shapiro-Wilk test has more power, we expect it to reject more often, at least when the null hypothesis is false (i.e., when the data are not Normally distributed). Meanwhile, when the null hypothesis is true, we would expect both the KS test and the Shapiro-Wilk test to falsely reject the null hypothesis about 5% of the time (because both are valid tests for the null hypothesis that the data are Normally distributed). Thus, in general, we would expect the Shapiro-Wilk test to reject more frequently than the KS test, as we have seen here.

  1. (5pts) Finally, we’re going to assess if energy_100g has a different distribution for Grade B and Grade D foods using a two-sample KS test. Use the following code to run a two-sample KS test:

ks.test(food.b$energy_100g, food.d$energy_100g)

##

## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

where you must appropriately define food.b. State your formal conclusion for this test; in your conclusion, be sure to mention what the null hypothesis is for this test.

From the above test, we see that we get a very small p-value that’s certainly less than 0.05. Thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the distribution of energy_100g is the same for Grade B and Grade D foods, thereby concluding that they differ. [Indeed, if we look back at the smoothed density plot we made in Question 2E, we see that these distributions have very different means, variances, and shape, so it is unsurprising that we reject the null hypothesis here.]
